UID:48b74f9b3fe34282@fed-nlrb-news.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260705T190802Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20200520
SUMMARY:[Federal Practice Areas] Rule Changes in Representation Cases - Ef
 fective May 31\, 2020
DESCRIPTION:May 20\, 2020\nOn May 31\, 2020 the National Labor Relations B
 oard  implemented in full the following rule changes :\nScheduling the h
 earing at least 14 days from issuance of the notice of hearing\;\nPosting 
 the notice of election within 5 days instead of 2 days\;\nChanges in timel
 ine for serving the non-petitioning party’s statement of position\;\nReq
 uiring petitioner to serve a responsive statement of position\;\nReinstate
 ment of Post-Hearing Briefs\;\nReinstating Regional Director discretion on
  the timing of a notice of election after the direction of an election\;\n
 Ballot impoundment procedures when a request for review is pending\;\nProh
 ibition on bifurcated requests for review\;\nCertain changes in formatting
  for pleadings and other documents\; and\nTerminology changes and defining
  days as “business” days.\nThe General Counsel has issued a guidance m
 emorandum regarding implementation of the rule.\nGC 20-07\n.\nThe remainin
 g five provisions of the December 2019 amendments\, are under review per 
 a recent U.S. District Court order.  These are:\nReinstitution of pre-el
 ection hearings for litigating eligibility issues\;\nTiming of the date of
  election\;\nVoter list timing\;\nElection observer eligibility\; and\nTim
 ing of Regional Director certification of representatives.\nhttps://www.nl
 rb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/rule-changes-in-representation-cases-effec
 tive-may-31-2020
URL:https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/rule-changes-in-represen
 tation-cases-effective-may-31-2020
CATEGORIES:Federal Practice Areas
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:b34ef92dcb7353de@fed-nlrb-news.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260705T190802Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20200331
SUMMARY:[Federal Practice Areas] NLRB Finalizes Rulemaking to Protect Empl
 oyee Free Choice
DESCRIPTION:March 31\, 2020\nWashington D.C\n.- The National Labor Relatio
 ns Board (NLRB) has finalized a series of amendments to Part 103 of its Ru
 les and Regulations. The Board believes that these amendments better prote
 ct employees’ statutory right of free choice on questions concerning rep
 resentation. The final rule will be published in the Federal Register tomo
 rrow\, April 1\, 2020.\nThe amendments\, proposed by the Board on August 1
 2\, 2019 and as modified in the final rule\, include:\nBlocking Charge Pol
 icy\n: The amendment replaces the current blocking charge policy with eith
 er a vote-and-count or a vote-and-impound procedure. Elections would no lo
 nger be blocked by pending unfair labor practice charges\, but the ballots
  would be either counted or impounded—depending on the nature of the cha
 rges—until the charges are resolved. Regardless of the nature of the cha
 rge\, the certification of results (including\, where appropriate\, a cert
 ification of representative) shall not issue until there is a final dispos
 ition of the charge and its effect\, if any\, on the election petition.\nV
 oluntary Recognition Bar\n: The amendment returns to the rule of\nDana Cor
 p.\n\, 351 NLRB 434 (2007). For voluntary recognition under Section 9(a) o
 f the Act to bar a subsequent representation petition—and for a post-rec
 ognition collective-bargaining agreement to have contract-bar effect—uni
 t employees must receive notice that voluntary recognition has been grante
 d and are given a 45-day open period within which to file an election peti
 tion. The amendment applies to a voluntary recognition on or after the eff
 ective date of the rule.\nSection 9(a) Recognition in the Construction Ind
 ustry\n: The amendment states that in the construction industry\, where ba
 rgaining relationships established under Section 8(f) cannot bar petitions
  for a Board election\, proof of a Section 9(a) relationship will require 
 positive evidence of majority employee support and cannot be based on cont
 ract language alone\, overruling\nStaunton Fuel\n\, 33\nhttps://www.nlrb.g
 ov/news-outreach/news-story/nlrb-finalizes-rulemaking-to-protect-employee-
 free-choice
URL:https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/nlrb-finalizes-rulemakin
 g-to-protect-employee-free-choice
CATEGORIES:Federal Practice Areas
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:12eaeb7428c45eef@fed-nlrb-news.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260705T190802Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20200324
SUMMARY:[Federal Practice Areas] Board Delays Implementation of Modificati
 ons to Representation Case Procedures
DESCRIPTION:March 24\, 2020\nWashington D.C. – The National Labor Relati
 ons Board announces that\, to facilitate the resolution of legal challenge
 s\, it is postponing the effective date of its final rule modifying the Ag
 ency’s Representation Case Procedures from April 16\, 2020 to May 31\, 2
 020. The notice will be published later in the week.\nThe Board published 
 the final rule on December 13\, 2019. The modifications contained in the f
 inal rule retain the essentials of the Agency’s existing representation 
 rules but allow for a fairer and more-efficient election process.\nThe fin
 al rule includes clarifications to procedures prior to an election that be
 tter ensure the opportunity for litigation and resolution of unit scope an
 d voter eligibility issues. The changes also permit parties additional tim
 e to comply with the various pre-election requirements instituted in 2014.
 \nEstablished in 1935\, the National Labor Relations Board is an independe
 nt federal agency that protects employees and employers\, and unions from 
 unfair labor practices and protects the right of private sector employees 
 to join together\, with or without a union\, to improve wages\, benefits a
 nd working conditions. The NLRB conducts hundreds of workplace elections a
 nd investigates thousands of unfair labor practice charges each year.\nhtt
 ps://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/board-delays-implementation-of-
 modifications-to-representation-case
URL:https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/board-delays-implementat
 ion-of-modifications-to-representation-case
CATEGORIES:Federal Practice Areas
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a1b875aeb9e3e331@fed-nlrb-news.maine-government-feeds
